'''J<U+00E9>r<U+00E9>my M<U+00E9>nez''' ({{IPA-fr|<U+0292>e.<U+0281>e.mi me.n<U+025B>z}} ; born 7 May 1987) is a French international [[Association football|footballer]] who currently plays for [[Serie A]] club [[A.C. Milan]] and the [[France national football team|France national team]] as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]]. M<U+00E9>nez has been described as an [[ambidexterity|ambidextrous]] technically skilled playmaker with undeniable pace.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.maxifoot.fr/football/article-1640.htm | title = M<U+00E9>nez, le prodige |date=25 January 2005 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Maxifoot | language = French}}</ref>

M<U+00E9>nez began his career spending time with various clubs in the [[<U+00CE>le-de-France (region)|<U+00CE>le-de-France]] [[Regions of France|region]] such as the Centre de Formation de Paris and CSF Br<U+00E9>tigny. In 2001, he secured a move to [[FC Sochaux-Montb<U+00E9>liard|Sochaux]] and spent four years in the club's youth academy. In March 2004, M<U+00E9>nez became the youngest professional football player in the history of [[Ligue 1]] after signing a professional contract and made his professional debut in the [[2004<U+2013>05 Ligue 1|2004<U+2013>05 season]]. With Sochaux, he played [[UEFA|European]] football for the first time after participating in the [[2004<U+2013>05 UEFA Cup|2004<U+2013>05 edition]] of the [[UEFA Cup]]. After two seasons at the club, he joined [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]]. At Monaco, M<U+00E9>nez developed into a play-making midfielder under the tutelage of [[Brazil]]ian manager [[Ricardo Gomes]]. After two successful seasons in [[Monaco]], he signed for [[Serie A]] club [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] on a four-year contract. With Roma, M<U+00E9>nez featured in the [[UEFA Champions League]] for the first time and scored 12 goals in over 100 appearances with the club. In July 2011, after three seasons with Roma, M<U+00E9>nez returned to France signing a three-year contract with [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]].

M<U+00E9>nez is a former [[France national youth football team|French youth international]] and has represented his nation at every level for which he was eligible. Prior to playing for the [[France national football team|senior team]], he played in the [[France national under-17 football team|under-17 team]] that won the [[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship]]. M<U+00E9>nez made his senior international debut in August 2010 in a friendly match against [[Norway national football team|Norway]].

==Club career==

===Early career===
M<U+00E9>nez was born on 7 May 1987 in [[Longjumeau]], a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the southern suburbs of Paris, to a family that was originally from [[Brittany]]. As a child, he grew up in [[Vitry-sur-Seine]], not far from his birthplace, and supported hometown club [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]].<ref name ="menez_early">{{cite news |url=http://www.omarlecheri.net/tandem6/Menez.htm | title = J<U+00E9>r<U+00E9>my M<U+00E9>nez: de Vitry <U+00E0> Monaco |date=8 March 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Omar Le Cherie |language = French}}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez became attracted to football through his father and older brother who were football players themselves. M<U+00E9>nez began his career at local club CA Vitry. After a year at the club, M<U+00E9>nez joined the Centre de Formation de Paris, a youth sporting club designed to cater only to football players under the age of 19.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cffp.fr/accueilcffp_histoireducffp.htm | title = Histoire du CFFP | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Centre de Formation de Paris | language = French}}</ref> While at C.F.F.P, M<U+00E9>nez developed and honed his technical skills and was placed into the [[playmaker]] position by his coaches. After five years at the academy, he departed the club after developing friction with the academy coaches.<ref name ="menez_early"/> After leaving CFFP, M<U+00E9>nez joined CSF Br<U+00E9>tigny, a local Parisian club that also trained [[France national football team|French internationals]] [[Patrice Evra]] and [[Jimmy Briand]]. He spent only a year at the club before securing a move to professional club [[FC Sochaux-Montb<U+00E9>liard|Sochaux]] in Franche-Comt<U+00E9>.

===Sochaux===
Upon his arrival at Sochaux, M<U+00E9>nez entered the club's youth academy and began attending the sports department's elite high school, Vignes de Seloncourt, with ambitions of becoming an accountant.<ref name ="menez_way">{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/news/newsid=275245.html | title = M<U+00E9>nez shows Sochaux the way |date= 28 January 2005 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]]}}</ref> While in the club's academy, M<U+00E9>nez was adept both on and off the field earning good grades in school.<ref name ="menez_early"/> On 24 March 2004, at the age of 16, he signed his first professional contract with Sochaux, agreeing to a three-year deal until June 2007. Upon signing the contract, he became the youngest professional football player in the history of [[Ligue 1]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football365.fr/france/infos-clubs/sochaux/article_27532_Sochaux-Jeremy-Menez-passe-pro.shtml | title = Sochaux: J<U+00E9>r<U+00E9>my M<U+00E9>nez passe pro |date= 24 March 2004 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Football 365 | language = French}}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez was subsequently promoted to the club's senior team and assigned the number 26 shirt by manager [[Guy Lacombe]]. Prior to signing his contract, M<U+00E9>nez drew strong interest from English clubs [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. The latter club's manager, [[Alex Ferguson]], was later accused by Sochaux's former president [[Jean-Claude Plessis]] of [[tapping up]] M<U+00E9>nez. Dassier accused Ferguson of meeting with the player's parents in Paris and offering them financial favors. Manchester United denied the accusations.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.manutd.com/default.sps?pagegid={04B0BD8D-A3EC-4900-A6D6-69EC18C57BB0}&newsid=144864&page=1 | title = Fergie in "tap" row |date= 25 January 2005 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Manchester United F.C.]] }}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez traveled to [[Manchester]] and visited the team's facilities and [[Old Trafford]], the club's stadium, before deciding to remain in France.<ref name="menez_way"/>

On 7 August 2004, M<U+00E9>nez made his professional debut in the club's opening match of the [[2004<U+2013>05 Ligue 1|2004<U+2013>05 season]] against [[AC Ajaccio]]. He started the match and played 57 minutes before being substituted for in a 1<U+2013>0 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2004/2005&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J01&num_ordre=9 | title = Sochaux v. Ajaccio Match Report |date= 7 August 2004 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> Despite being so young, M<U+00E9>nez was a regular within the team, often rotating between the bench and starting eleven. On 20 November, he scored his first professional goal in a 3<U+2013>1 victory over Monaco.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2004/2005&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J15&num_ordre=5 | title = Monaco v. Sochaux Match Report |date= 20 November 2004 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> Two months later, M<U+00E9>nez became the youngest player in league history to score a [[hat trick]] after recording one in the team's 4<U+2013>0 victory over [[FC Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]].<ref name="menez_way"/> He scored the goals in a seven-minute span to assure Sochaux of victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2004/2005&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J22&num_ordre=9 | title = Sochaux v. Bordeaux Match Report |date= 22 January 2005 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez was a regular during the team's [[2004<U+2013>05 UEFA Cup]] campaign, appearing in six matches with the club.<ref name=uc0405>{{cite web|title=J<U+00E9>r<U+00E9>my M<U+00E9>nez profile|url=http://www.uefa.com/teamsandplayers/players/player=72715/profile/index.html|publisher=UEFA|accessdate=19 September 2014}}</ref>  Sochaux suffered elimination in the Round of 32 at the hands of [[Greece|Greek]] club [[Olympiakos FC|Olympiakos]]. Following the season, M<U+00E9>nez was nominated for the [[National Union of Professional Football Players|UNFP]] [[Troph<U+00E9>es UNFP du football#Young Player of the Year|Young Player of the Year]] award but lost out to [[FC Nantes|Nantes]] [[midfielder]] [[J<U+00E9>r<U+00E9>my Toulalan]].

For the [[2005<U+2013>06 Ligue 1|2005<U+2013>06 season]], M<U+00E9>nez switched to the number 11 shirt and was given a more prominent role within the team by new manager [[Dominique Bijotat]]. He appeared in 31 league matches, fifth-best on the team, and scored three goals. M<U+00E9>nez scored his first goal on 15 October 2005 in a 1<U+2013>1 draw against Bordeaux.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2005/2006&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J11&num_ordre=2 | title = Bordeaux v. Sochaux Match Report |date= 15 October 2005 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> At the beginning of the new year, M<U+00E9>nez scored his final two goals in another 1<U+2013>1 draw with [[OGC Nice|Nice]] and a 4<U+2013>0 victory over [[AS Saint-<U+00C9>tienne|Saint-<U+00C9>tienne]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2005/2006&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J21&num_ordre=8 | title = Sochaux v. Nice Match Report |date= 11 January 2006 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2005/2006&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J23&num_ordre=8 | title = Sochaux v. Saint-<U+00C9>tienne Match Report |date= 21 January 2006 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> Sochaux finished the season in a disappointing 15th position after finishing the four previous seasons in the top ten. This led M<U+00E9>nez to become unsettled and to declare his desire to leave the club. On 8 June 2006, Sochaux chairman Dassier announced that he would consider offers for the player with Ligue 1 clubs Paris Saint-Germain, [[Girondins de Bordeaux|Bordeaux]], Monaco, and English club Arsenal reported to be interested.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11670_2379703,00.html | title = Sochaux take M<U+00E9>nez stance |date= 8 June 2006 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | language = French}}</ref>

===Monaco===
On 22 June 2006, Sochaux announced on its website that it had reached an agreement with fellow Ligue 1 club [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] for the transfer of M<U+00E9>nez. He signed a four-year contract. The transfer fee was undisclosed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/news/player_archive/0,19889,11816_1_123953_1,00.html | title = Monaco bag Menez |date= 22 June 2006| accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez was given the number 10 shirt by manager [[L<U+00E1>szl<U+00F3> B<U+00F6>l<U+00F6>ni]] and inserted into his preferred left-winger position. He made his club debut on 19 August in the team's 1<U+2013>1 draw with [[Stade Rennais F.C.|Rennes]], appearing as a substitute.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J03&num_ordre=7 | title = Rennes v. Monaco Match Report |date= 19 August 2006 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel }}</ref> On 30 September, M<U+00E9>nez scored his first goal for the club in a 2<U+2013>1 win over [[Le Mans Football Club|Le Mans]], netting the game-winner ten minutes from time.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J08&num_ordre=5 | title = Monaco v. Le Mans Match Report |date= 30 September 2006 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> Following the firing of B<U+00F6>l<U+00F6>ni and the arrival of new manager [[Ricardo Gomes]], M<U+00E9>nez struggled to get consistent playing time and grew frustrated, which led to interest abroad from Manchester United and [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11667_2792810,00.html | title = English giants track M<U+00E9>nez |date= 10 October 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref> However, on 11 November, he was re-inserted into the starting lineup and scored the equalizing goal in a 2<U+2013>2 draw with Lorient.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J14&num_ordre=4 | title = Monaco v. Lorient Match Report |date= 18 November 2006 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez maintained his form into the new year, but struggled for fitness in February due to a [[groin]] injury. The injury required surgery and M<U+00E9>nez missed two months of play.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11800_3369880,00.html | title = M<U+00E9>nez scare for Monaco |date= 31 March 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref> He returned to the team in April and scored goals in three straight matches against [[Lille OSC|Lille]], [[Valenciennes FC|Valenciennes]], and [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J33&num_ordre=4 | title = Monaco v. Lille Match Report |date= 21 April 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J34&num_ordre=10 | title = Valenciennes v. Monaco Match Report |date= 28 April 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J35&num_ordre=4 | title = Monaco v. Marseille Match Report |date= 6 May 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez finished the 2006<U+2013>07 campaign by scoring the only goal in a win over the champions [[Olympique Lyonnais|Lyon]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2006/2007&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J37&num_ordre=4 | title = Monaco v. Lyon Match Report |date= 19 May 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref>

Despite summer interest from [[Premier League]] clubs, M<U+00E9>nez opted to remain at Monaco. In the [[2007<U+2013>08 Ligue 1|2007<U+2013>08 campaign]], he scored his first goal in the team's 3<U+2013>0 victory over his former club Sochaux.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11674_3961687,00.html | title = M<U+00E9>nez likely to stay put |date= 10 August 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J04&num_ordre=9 | title = Sochaux v. Monaco Match Report |date= 18 August 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> The following week, he netted again, this time in a 3<U+2013>1 win over Le Mans.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J05&num_ordre=4 | title = Monaco v. Le Mans Match Report |date= 25 August 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> On 15 December, M<U+00E9>nez scored a double in a 3<U+2013>1 victory against [[RC Lens|Lens]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J18&num_ordre=6 | title = Monaco v. Lens Match Report |date= 15 December 2007 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> It was his first multi-goal game since his hat trick three years prior. The following month, M<U+00E9>nez scored both of the team's goal in a 2<U+2013>0 away win against [[FC Metz|Metz]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuilleMatch.asp?saison=2007/2008&code_evt=&code_jr_tr=J21&num_ordre=6 | title = Metz v. Monaco Match Report |date= 19 January 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | language = French}}</ref> On 23 February 2008, he suffered an injury in a league match against Paris-Saint Germain, which led to him leaving the match at half-time. The injury was discovered to be serious and M<U+00E9>nez missed three months before returning for the final two matches of the season making obligatory substitute appearances.

===Roma===
After featuring in Monaco's first three league matches of the season, it was reported on 27 August 2008 that M<U+00E9>nez had signed a four-year contract with Italian club [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]. The transfer fee was priced at <U+20AC>10.5&nbsp;million with Monaco set to receive another <U+20AC>1.5&nbsp;million in incentives.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,11800_4057266,00.html | title = M<U+00E9>nez joins Roma |date=27 August 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] }}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez was announced as the replacement for departed wingers [[Mancini (Brazilian footballer)|Mancini]] and [[Ludovic Giuly]] and selected the number 24 shirt, the former number of club legend [[Marco Delvecchio]]. He made his debut for the club on 31 August in the team's league match against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]], appearing as a substitute in the 63rd minute.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=251218&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = AS Roma 1 <U+2013> 1 Napoli |date=31 August 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez made his [[UEFA Champions League]] debut in the team's group stage match against Bordeaux, playing 51 minutes in a 3<U+2013>1 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=254674&cc=5901&league=UEFA.CHAMPIONS | title = Baptista's deadly double |date=1 October 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 6 December, he scored his first goal for the club in a 1<U+2013>0 victory over [[Chievo Verona|Chievo]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=251392&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = Chievo Verona 0<U+2013>1 AS Roma |date=6 December 2008 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> For the majority of the campaign, however, M<U+00E9>nez struggled for consistent playing time, rarely lasting an entire match and often starting on the bench for consecutive matches under [[Luciano Spalletti]]. On 24 May 2009, he appeared as a substitute in the 75th minute against [[A.C. Milan|Milan]]. After five minutes on the field, M<U+00E9>nez scored a goal to put Roma up 2<U+2013>1. The capital club went on to win the match 3<U+2013>2.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=251572&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = AS Roma 3<U+2013>2 Torino |date=31 May 2009 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> The following week, he started the match and scored a goal in a 3<U+2013>2 win over [[Torino F.C.|Torino]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=251563&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = AC Milan 2<U+2013>3 AS Roma |date=24 May 2009 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> He was later substituted out in the 59th minute.

For the [[2009<U+2013>10 Serie A|2009<U+2013>10 season]]. M<U+00E9>nez switched to the unusual number 94 shirt. He scored against Milan his first goal on 18 October 2009.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=278467&cc=5901&league=ITA.1 | title = Pato seals nervy win for Milan |date=19 October 2009 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 6 January 2010, he drew the ire of new manager [[Claudio Ranieri]] and several teammates, who criticized him for his substitute appearance against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]] in which he gave a somewhat lackadaisical effort. Following the criticism, M<U+00E9>nez stated: <U+201C>I touched the lowest point of my career in that game away to Cagliari." and <U+201C>My teammates were right to criticise me.<U+201D><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.football-italia.net/blogs/jh110.html | title = From a boy to M<U+00E9>nez |date=30 July 2010 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=Football Italia }}</ref> On 11 January, M<U+00E9>nez issued an apology to coach Ranieri and his teammates and brushed off rumors of him issuing a transfer request by declaring himself fully committed to the team. On 30 January, [[midfielder]] [[Simone Perrotta]] stated that M<U+00E9>nez simply needed a confidence boost.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.asromalive.com/perrotta-ranieri-nazionale-roma-jeremy-menez/19300/ | title = Perrotta: "Ranieri, la Nazionale, la mia Roma e J<U+00E9>r<U+00E9>my M<U+00E9>nez: dico io" |date=30 January 2010 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=AS Roma Live | language= <U+2013> Italian}}</ref> After appearing as a substitute for four consecutive matches after the Cagliari match, M<U+00E9>nez made his first start since December 2009 in a league match against [[Calcio Catania|Catania]] on 21 February. He capped the return by assisting on the game-winning goal scored by [[Mirko Vu<U+010D>ini<U+0107>]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=278498&cc=5901 | title = AS Roma 1 <U+2013> 0 Catania |date=21 February 2010 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez finished the campaign by starting eight of the final ten league matches as Roma finished the season in second place and qualified for the UEFA Champions League.

In the [[2010<U+2013>11 Serie A|2010<U+2013>11 season]], M<U+00E9>nez began the season as a starter under Ranieri after his successful end to the previous season. However, despite being a starter, Ranieri continued to undermine M<U+00E9>nez's durability as he consistently substituted the player out in every match he started. On 3 November, M<U+00E9>nez scored his first goal of the campaign in a 3<U+2013>2 Champions League victory over [[Switzerland|Swiss]] club [[FC Basel|Basel]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/matches/season=2011/round=2000118/match=2002865/index.html | title = Roma hang on to make amends at Basel |date= 3 November 2010 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] }}</ref> A week later, he assisted on a [[Marco Borriello]] goal in a 3<U+2013>2 win over [[A.C.F. Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304797&cc=5901 | title = AS Roma 3<U+2013>2 Fiorentina |date= 10 November 2010 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 13 November, for the first time in the season, M<U+00E9>nez played an entire match after playing in a 1<U+2013>1 draw with [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304771&cc=5901 | title = Totti penalty earns draw |date= 13 November 2010 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> In the team's next league match against [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]], he scored his first league goal and also assisted on a goal in a 2<U+2013>0 win.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304782&cc=5901 | title = Roma up to third |date= 20 November 2010 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> After going scoreless in December, on 22 January 2011, M<U+00E9>nez scored the final goal in a 3<U+2013>0 win over [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304777&cc=5901 | title = Ranieri's men put the pressure on Milan |date= 22 January 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 16 February, M<U+00E9>nez scored a goal in Roma's first leg of its Champions League first knockout round tie with [[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] combatants [[FC Shakhtar Donetsk|Shakhtar Donetsk]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/matches/season=2011/round=2000119/match=2003751/index.html | title = Shakhtar surge too much for Roma |date= 16 February 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] }}</ref> Five days later, Ranieri resigned from his position as manager and replaced with [[Vincenzo Montella]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/SPORT/football/02/20/football.italy.ranieri.roma/index.html | title = Ranieri quits as Roma coach after fourth successive defeat |date= 21 February 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 |publisher=CNN }}</ref> Under Montella, M<U+00E9>nez appeared in the manager's first three matches as a substitute. On 13 March, he made his first start under Montella in a league match against [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], but was substitute out after 55 minutes.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=304900&cc=5901 | title = Totti brace seals derby win |date= 13 March 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> On 23 March, in an interview with French newspaper ''[[L'Equipe]]'', M<U+00E9>nez admitted that he was frustrated with his playing time under Montella.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.espnstar.com/football/serie-a/news/detail/item600015/Menez-agent-reveals-Montella-problem/ | title = M<U+00E9>nez agent reveals Montella problem |date= 24 March 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=ESPN }}</ref> The frustration reached its zenith when, on 21 April, M<U+00E9>nez and Montella got into an altercation during a morning training session after Montella reportedly "spent a quarter of an hour berating the France international" for his lack of commitment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.corrieredellosport.it/calcio/serie_a/roma/2011/04/21-168038/Auto+Menez+danneggiata%3A+sassi+contro+il+parabrezza | title = Auto M<U+00E9>nez danneggiata: sassi contro il parabrezza |date= 21 April 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=[[Corriere dello Sport <U+2013> Stadio]] | language = Italian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.daily-calcio.com/index.php?option=news&task=viewarticle&sid=30861 | title = Montella bust up with M<U+00E9>nez |date= 21 April 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=Daily-Calcio }}</ref> Later that night, following the team's [[Coppa Italia]] tie with [[F.C. Internazionale Milano|Internazionale]], while leaving the [[Stadio Olimpico]] in his vehicle, M<U+00E9>nez was attacked by stone-throwing "thugs," which resulted in his car [[windshield]] being smashed.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/2011/04/21-120700/Roma%3A+sassi+contro+l%27auto+di+Menez | title = Roma: sassi contro l'auto di M<U+00E9>nez |date= 21 April 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=[[Tuttosport]] | language = Italian }}</ref>

=== Paris Saint-Germain ===
[[File:Menez et Kombouar<U+00E9>.png|thumb|200px|M<U+00E9>nez with manager [[Antoine Kombouar<U+00E9>]] in 2011.]]
On 25 July 2011, French club [[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.|Paris Saint-Germain]] confirmed that the club had signed M<U+00E9>nez to a three-year contract.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.lequipe.fr/Football/breves2011/20110725_144853_matuidi-et-menez-au-psg-off.html | title = Matuidi et M<U+00E9>nez au PSG (off.) | date = 25 July 2011 | work=[[L'Equipe]] | accessdate =25 July 2011 | language = French}}</ref> The transfer fee was <U+20AC>8&nbsp;million plus possible future incentives.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2011/soccer/wires/07/25/2080.ap.soc.psg.signings.2nd.ld.writethru.0394/ | title = PSG signs M<U+00E9>nez, Matuidi to spur title ambitions | date = 25 July 2011 |work=Sports Illustrated | accessdate =25 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://109.75.174.100/~asroma/downloads/corporate_investor/1311672014_260711_menez.pdf | title = Cessione a titolo definitivo dei diritti alle prestazioni sportive des calciatore J<U+00E9>r<U+00E9>my M<U+00E9>nez | date = 25 July 2011 | work=[[A.S. Roma]] | accessdate =1 August 2011 | language = French }}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez was presented to the media the same day alongside fellow new signing and international teammate [[Blaise Matuidi]] and was assigned the number 7 shirt.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.psg.fr/fr/Article/003001/Article/54398/Matuidi-et-Menez-s-engagent-avec-le-PSG | title = Matuidi et M<U+00E9>nez s<U+2019>engagent avec le PSG | date = 25 July 2011 | work=[[Paris Saint-Germain F.C.]] | accessdate =25 July 2011 | language = French}}</ref> He made his club debut for the team in its 1<U+2013>0 defeat to the [[New York Red Bulls]] at the [[Emirates Cup]]. M<U+00E9>nez made his competitive debut for Paris Saint-Germain on 6 August 2011 in the team's opening 1<U+2013>0 league defeat to [[FC Lorient|Lorient]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Paris Saint-Germain v. Lorient Match Report | url = http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/74378 | date = 6 August 2011 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | accessdate =18 August 2011 | language = French}}</ref> The following week, he assisted on the team's opening goal, scored by [[K<U+00E9>vin Gameiro]], in a 1<U+2013>1 draw with Rennes.<ref>{{cite news | title = Rennes v. Paris Saint-Germain Match Report | url = http://www.lfp.fr/ligue1/feuille_match/74384 | date = 13 August 2011 | publisher=Ligue de Football Professionnel | accessdate =18 August 2011 | language = French}}</ref> On 18 August 2011, in PSG's first leg [[2011<U+2013>12 UEFA Europa League|UEFA Europa League]] playoff round tie against [[Luxembourg]]er club [[FC Differdange 03|Differdange]], M<U+00E9>nez scored the final goal for the team in a 4<U+2013>0 away win. He also assisted on a goal in the victory.<ref>{{cite news | title = Differdange v. PSG Match Report | url = http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2012/matches/round=2000271/match=2007211/postmatch/index.html | date = 18 August 2011 | work=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] | accessdate =18 August 2011 }}</ref> Three days later, he again assisted Gameiro for a goal in a 2<U+2013>1 win over [[Valenciennes FC|Valenciennes]], helping Paris Saint-Germain earn its first league win of the season. On 28 August, M<U+00E9>nez netted his first league goal for the club away to [[Toulouse F.C.|Toulouse]]; Paris Saint-Germain won the match 3<U+2013>1.

Under the guidance of coaches [[Antoine Kombouar<U+00E9>]] and later [[Carlo Ancelotti]], M<U+00E9>nez enjoyed a strong campaign which saw him deliver seven goals and 12 assists in 33 league appearances for PSG, a career best for him. On 4 December 2011, during a 3<U+2013>2 home league victory against [[AJ Auxerre]], M<U+00E9>nez scored PSG's 2,000th goal in top flight football.

In the [[2012-13 Ligue 1]], M<U+00E9>nez was used less prolificly in domestic league matches. With two goals and two assists in five European appearances, however, he has been one of his club's main actors in their [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] efforts, developing a strong understanding on the pitch with new star striker [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi<U+0107>]], another former [[Serie A]] player.

=== AC Milan ===

On 11 June 2014, Italian club [[A.C. Milan|AC Milan]] confirmed that the club had signed M<U+00E9>nez on a three-year contract.<ref>https://twitter.com/acmilan/status/476822930161405953</ref> On 31 August 2014, M<U+00E9>nez scored a penalty on his debut for Milan against [[SS Lazio|Lazio]]. Menez went on to score two goals against [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] helping Milan win the game. His first goal in this game was from a penalty, and the second goal was a beautifully worked backheel finish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/italian-serie-a/match/403818/parma-ac-milan/report |title=Jeremy Menez stars as AC Milan edge nine-goal thriller with Parma |work=ESPNFC |date=14 September 2014 |accessdate=14 September 2014 }}</ref>

==International career==
===Youth===
M<U+00E9>nez has earned caps with all of [[France national youth football team|France's youth teams]]. He is a member of the group, commonly known as the ''G<U+00E9>n<U+00E9>ration 1987'', that produced current internationals [[Hatem Ben Arfa]], [[Karim Benzema]], and [[Samir Nasri]], alongside himself.
M<U+00E9>nez made his youth international debut with the [[France national under-16 football team|under-16 team]] on 11 December 2002 in a [[Exhibition match|friendly match]] against [[Greece national football team|Greece]], playing alongside Nasri and Ben Arfa. In the match, M<U+00E9>nez scored the fifth goal of a 6<U+2013>1 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/40021.shtml | title = La France termine l'ann<U+00E9>e en beaut<U+00E9> face <U+00E0> la Gr<U+00E8>ce (6<U+2013>1) |date= 11 December 2002 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> At the 2003 Aegean Cup in [[Turkey]], he scored goals in three consecutive matches. M<U+00E9>nez scored goals against the [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] and [[Israel national football team|Israel]] and netted his final goal in the third-place match against [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/41839.shtml | title = La France se reprend face <U+00E0> Isra<U+00EB>l (3<U+2013>1) |date= 8 January 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/42113.shtml | title = Les tricolores dominent l'Ukraine (5<U+2013>0) |date= 10 January 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/42275.shtml | title = La France termine troisi<U+00E8>me (3<U+2013>2) |date= 12 January 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> At the [[Montaigu Tournament|Tournio de Montaigu]], M<U+00E9>nez scored three goals, second-best on the team behind Ben Arfa. He scored a goal in the team's 8<U+2013>0 win over [[Gabon national football team|Gabon]] in the team's opening group match and, in the following match, scored the opening goal in the team's 3<U+2013>0 win over [[Russia national football team|Russia]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/51364.shtml | title = Entr<U+00E9>e en mati<U+00E8>re r<U+00E9>ussie face au Gabon (8<U+2013>0) |date= 16 April 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/51476.shtml | title = La France poursuit sur sa lanc<U+00E9>e (3<U+2013>0) |date= 17 April 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> In the team's final group stage match against [[England national under-16 football team|England]], M<U+00E9>nez netted another goal in a 3<U+2013>1 victory.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/51666.shtml | title = La France gagne (3<U+2013>1) et se retrouve en finale! |date= 19 April 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> At a regional tournament in [[Salerno]], Italy, M<U+00E9>nez led the team to the title by scoring a double in the final match against [[Italy national football team|the hosts]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/56535.shtml | title = La France victorieuse <U+00E0> Salerne! |date= 19 June 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> He also scored two goals in the group matches against [[Japan national football team|Japan]] and [[Finland national football team|Finland]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/54633.shtml | title = Les Tricolores d<U+00E9>butent bien face au Japon (3<U+2013>2) |date= 15 June 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m16ans/56205.shtml | title = La France bat la Finlande (3<U+2013>1) |date= 17 June 2003 | accessdate =7 August 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> M<U+00E9>nez finished the under-16 campaign with 14 appearances and a team-leading 12 goals.

With the [[France national under-17 football team|under-17 team]], M<U+00E9>nez, Ben Arfa, and Nasri were joined by [[Karim Benzema]] and tasked with the goal of winning the [[2004 UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship]] on home soil. M<U+00E9>nez made his debut with the team in the opening match of the season against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]]. In the Tournio de [[Val-de-Marne]], he scored one goal. France were crowned champions without conceding a goal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/selections/m17ans/actualite/72264.shtml | title = Philippe Bergeroo : "Un tournoi riche d'enseignements" |date= 1 November 2003 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> At the 2004 UEFA European Under-17 Football Championship, M<U+00E9>nez contributed to the team's winning the competition by scoring two goals, netting one against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] in the group stage and a second in the semi-finals against [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75060/index.html | title = France lifted by late goals |date= 4 May 2004 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/under17/history/season=2004/round=1658/match=75064/index.html | title = Flamboyant hosts earn final chance |date= 9 May 2004 | accessdate =16 June 2010 | publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] }}</ref> In total with the under-17s, he made 17 appearances and scored six goals. Due to increased playing time at his parent club Sochaux, M<U+00E9>nez's stint with the [[France national under-18 football team|under-18 team]] was uneventful. M<U+00E9>nez did appear with the team at the [[2005 UEFA-CAF Meridian Cup]], scoring five goals in four matches as France were crowned champions.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/meridian/news/kind=1/newsid=798075.html | title = 2005: Europe extend Meridian domination |date= 1 January 2009 | accessdate =26 April 2011 | publisher=[[UEFA|Union of European Football Associations]] }}</ref>

The foursome of Ben Arfa, Nasri, Benzema, and M<U+00E9>nez returned to international play together for [[France national under-19 football team|under-19]] duty. The four were joined by [[Issiar Dia]], [[Blaise Matuidi]], and [[Serge Gakp<U+00E9>]] with the objective of winning the [[2006 UEFA European Under-19 Football Championship]]. In the first round of qualification for the tournament, M<U+00E9>nez went scoreless as France advanced through the round undefeated. In the final round of qualification, he scored a double against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] in a 4<U+2013>0 win. However, despite finishing the round undefeated, France were eliminated after being beaten on points by [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland]]. M<U+00E9>nez was absent from the [[France national under-21 football team|under-21]] team during his early eligibility term but made his debut on 25 May 2008 in the team's 2<U+2013>1 friendly match win over the [[Netherlands national under-21 football team|Netherlands]]. He went months without a call-up before finally returning to the team ahead of the important two-legged playoff against [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]] in qualification for the [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship]] in October 2008. M<U+00E9>nez appeared in both legs as France were defeated 2<U+2013>1 on aggregate. The 1<U+2013>0 loss in the second leg eliminated France from the competition and also ended M<U+00E9>nez's under-21 career.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=41 | title = France v. Germany Match Report |date= 15 October 2008 | accessdate =7 January 2011 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref>

[[File:J.M<U+00E9>nez Euro 2012.jpg|thumb|250px|right|M<U+00E9>nez (right) playing for [[France national football team|France]] against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] at [[UEFA Euro 2012]].]]
===Senior===
On 5 August 2010, M<U+00E9>nez was called up to the [[France national football team|senior team]] for the first time by new manager [[Laurent Blanc]] for the team's [[Exhibition match|friendly match]] against [[Norway national football team|Norway]] on 11 August 2010.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2010/aug/05/karim-benzema-hatem-ben-arfa-france | title = Karim Benzema and Hatem Ben Arfa in Laurent Blanc's first France squad | date = 5 August 2010 | work=[[Guardian Media Group]] | accessdate =21 February 2011 }}</ref> He made his international debut in the match starting on the right wing as France were defeated 2<U+2013>1.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fff.fr/servfff/fiche_joueur_new/match.php?id_match=1285 | title = 11/08/2010 Equipe de France A <U+2013> Amical  |date= 11 August 2010 | accessdate =23 February 2011 | publisher=French Football Federation | language = French}}</ref> On 9 February 2011, M<U+00E9>nez assisted on the only goal, scored by Benzema, in the team's 1<U+2013>0 win over [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] at the [[Stade de France]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/international-friendlies/8315057/France-1-Brazil-0-match-report.html | title = France 1 Brazil 0: match report |date= 9 February 2011 | accessdate =26 April 2011 |work=The Daily Telegraph |location=UK }}</ref> After appearing regularly in qualifying for UEFA Euro 2012, on 29 May 2012, M<U+00E9>nez was named to the squad to participate in the competition.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/yoann-gourcuff-omitted-as-france-announce-euro-2012-squad-7800136.html|title=Yoann Gourcuff omitted as France announce Euro 2012 squad|date=29 May 2012 |work=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=3 June 2012 }}</ref> On 5 June, in the team's final warm-up friendly ahead of the European Championship, he scored his first international goal in a 4<U+2013>0 shutout win over [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/sns-rt-uk-soccer-friendly-francebre854193-20120605,0,7372040.story|title=Benzema, Ribery shine as France thrash Estonia|publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] |date= 5 June 2012 |accessdate=5 June 2012}}</ref> At UEFA Euro 2012, M<U+00E9>nez made his debut at a senior international competition on 15 June in the team's second group stage match against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]]. In the contest, he started and scored France's opening goal in a 2<U+2013>0 victory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2012/06/16/sports/soccer/euro-2012-after-rain-delay-france-shuts-out-ukraine.html|title=After Rain Delay, France Shuts Out Ukraine|publisher=[[New York Times]] |date= 15 June 2012 |accessdate=17 June 2012}}</ref>

